Scientists have found a way to detect related stars
Astrophysicists at the University of California, Santa Cruz have studied turbulent mixing and its effect on chemical homogeneity in star clusters.
It is expected that the discovery of experts will make it possible to search for related stars, that is, those that emerged from the same cluster.
The authors published the results of their research in the journal Nature, and a summary of them can be found on the university's website.
The reason for the uniform chemical composition of nearby stars is the turbulent mixing in gas clouds that precedes star formation.
Even if a newly born star then leaves the star cluster, its chemical composition can determine its place of birth and the region where related stars were formed.
Previously, scientists had doubts that the evolution of a star outside the cluster could lead to differences in its chemical content from that of relatives in the cluster.
The simulations conducted by astrophysicists show that such differences should not appear.
In their study, the researchers used a supercomputer to simulate two streams of interstellar gas that together formed a cloud.
Within a few million years, the object is transformed by its own gravity into a cluster in which protostars begin to form.
Scientists added tagging paints to the original gas streams and found that rapid turbulent mixing in the cloud achieved a high degree of chemical homogeneity.
According to astrophysicists, their research proves that it is possible to search for related stars by chemical composition, as well as to determine the possible regions of formation of such objects.
