Remembering the Very American Ideal that Labor Rights Are Human Rights
Congressmen Keith Ellison and John Lewis have proposed legislation that would protect union organizing as a civil right.
"Where unions are, there are middle-class jobs," said Ellison, a Minnesota Democrat who is co-chairman of the Congressional Progressive Caucus.
That is why I am proud to introduce the Employee Empowerment Act with civil rights icon John Lewis.
This groundbreaking bill would give workers the same legal opportunity to discriminate against trade unions as other forms of discrimination, deterring anti-union forces
Amending the Labor Relations Act to allow workers who face discrimination for organizing trade unions to seek justice in the civil courts - and to receive damages and punitive damages - is a reasonable and necessary initiative.
But this is certainly not a radical initiative - at least by American standards.
In fact, the best way to understand what Ellison, Lewis, and the bill's co-sponsors are proposing is to recall a very American thought.
Despite the attacks that unions have faced in recent years - in Wisconsin, Michigan, and other states across the country - Americans once supported countries around the world to embrace, expand, and respect labor rights.
There was a time, still remembered by millions of Americans, when that country simultaneously defended democracy, freedom of speech, freedom of the press, and the right to organize.
When the United States occupied Japan after World War II, General Douglas MacArthur and his aides helped the country adopt a constitution designed to ensure that Hideki Tojo's militarized autocracy was replaced by democracy.
Fully aware that workers and their unions had a role to play in shaping the new Japan, they included text that explicitly recognized that "the right of workers to organize, to bargain, and to act collectively is guaranteed."
When the United States occupied Germany after World War II, General Dwight David Eisenhower and his aides helped the Germans write a constitution that ensured that Adolf Hitler's fascism was replaced by a strong democracy.
Recognizing that workers would need to organize and be heard in the new state, the Germans included an article that explicitly stated: "The right to form associations for the purpose of protecting and improving working and economic conditions will be guaranteed to every individual and every profession or occupation.
Agreements that limit or seek to limit this right will have no legal force; measures aimed at this end will be deemed illegal.
When former first lady Eleanor Roosevelt chaired the International Commission on Human Rights, which drafted the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, to be adopted by the United Nations in 1948 as a global treaty, Roosevelt and the drafters included a guarantee that "everyone has the right to organize and join trade unions for the protection of his interests."
For generations, Americans took for granted the basic premise that labor rights are human rights.
When that country advised other countries on how to build civil and democratic societies, Americans explained that the right to organize trade unions - and to have the union participate as an equal partner in collective bargaining with corporations and government agencies - must be protected.
Now that those rights are under assault in America, it is wise, indeed, to return to the American ideal that working people should have the right to organize and to have their voices heard in a free and open society.
As the Reverend Martin Luther King Jr said fifty years ago:
History is a great teacher.
Everyone now knows that the trade union movement did not undermine the strength of the nation, but increased it.
By raising the living standards of millions, trade unions miraculously created a market for industry and lifted an entire nation to unimaginable levels of production.
Those who attack trade unions forget these simple truths, but history remembers them.
History remembers, as it should.
Formal recognition of labor rights as human rights - and expanded civil rights protections to prevent discrimination against union organizing - is long overdue.
Keith Ellison and John Lewis are reviving the ideals that have historically enlarged America and made the promise of democracy a reality.
Judge temporarily blocks law that could close all Louisiana abortion clinics
In the United States, a federal judge on Sunday temporarily blocked the enactment of a Louisiana law that supporters say will likely close all five abortion clinics in the state.
The measure, signed into law by Louisiana Governor Bobby Jindal in June and due to take effect on September 1, would require doctors who perform abortions to have the authority to receive patients at a hospital within 30 miles of their practice.
However, the judge's ruling means that, for the time being, doctors can continue to perform legal abortions while continuing to seek such authority.
"Plaintiffs will be allowed to work legally while continuing to act to obtain authorization," Judge John deGravells wrote in his ruling.
A hearing will be scheduled within a month, at which the judge will make a more permanent ruling on the law.
Abortion rights advocates welcomed the decision, the latest in a series of rulings against similar measures, saying it would give doctors more time to obtain hospital authorization.
"Today's ruling ensures that Louisiana women will be protected from an insidious law that seeks to deprive them of their health and rights," said Nancy Northup, president and chief executive of the Center for Reproductive Rights, which filed the stay-the-law lawsuit on behalf of three of the state's five clinics.
It was not immediately clear whether the decision applied to doctors from two clinics who were not plaintiffs in the case and also applied for admission authority.
Louisiana is among 11 states that have passed similar laws, and courts recently ruled such measures unconstitutional in Alabama and Mississippi.
Key parts of a Texas law that would have shut down most of the state's remaining clinics were blocked by a federal judge Friday.
Abortion rights advocates, along with the American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists and the American Medical Association, say admission authority laws impose medically unnecessary restrictions on doctors.
Abortion opponents counter that such measures are aimed at protecting women's health, though some have also pointed to their positive effect in closing clinics.
Only one doctor who performs abortions in Louisiana has hospital admission authority, the Center for Reproductive Rights said.
If all other doctors in the state were forced to stop performing the procedure, the doctor, fearing for his safety, would stop performing the procedure, the group said.
Criticizing the decision, Louisiana officials said they would not punish doctors who perform abortions while their applications for admission authority await a decision.
What will the introduction of quotas for domestic products lead to?
No less than half of the products in the assortment of retail chains for each type of goods should be made in Russia, says State Duma deputy from the Just Russia faction, Oleg Nilov.
The parliamentarian has prepared a bill aimed at introducing protective measures against domestic producers, writes the newspaper Izvestia.
The document will still be detailed to avoid possible discomfort for buyers.
This applies to goods that are not produced in Russia. For other product groups that are produced in Russia, the retailer will have to provide at least half of its shelves to domestic producers, "Nilov told the publication.
Together with the amendments to the article "On the Fundamentals of State Regulation of Trade Activities in the Russian Federation," the bill provides for amendments to the Tax Code, which establish a reduced VAT rate of 10% for the sale of products manufactured in Russia.
The idea of introducing a 50% quota in retail chains is part of a package of stimulus measures for Russian producers.
Several times more domestic goods will appear on the shelves.
However, the initiative can have both positive and negative effects, experts say.
According to Sergei Litvinenko, a lawyer for the Nalogovik company and a member of the independent expert centre Public Duma, the effect on the Russian economy, as well as on the domestic agricultural and food industries, will be positive and will lead to growth.
Agricultural producers, farmers, and small shops will benefit.
They will be able to sell more, which means that profits will rise.
In addition, they will have the right to dictate their terms and prices to retailers, because they will be forced to buy their goods.
Russian producers will be able to increase their activities and sales, which will lead to higher taxes than before.
This will increase budget revenues, create new jobs, expand some industries, develop some faster, and contribute to GDP growth.
Russia's dependence on foreign food will decrease several times, but not immediately, "the expert notes.
Previously, Russian enterprises were often unable to make their way onto the shelves of local stores because of high competition from their foreign counterparts.
Now, with the imposition of the embargo, that niche has been liberated and we can breathe a sigh of relief.
But it should not be forgotten that, after all the necessary approvals and sanitary inspections, foodstuffs from Latin America, Turkey, and Serbia will enter the Russian market.
In other words, there is now a "moment of calm," when the old players have already left and the new ones have not yet arrived.
Almost a month later, we can talk about increased demand for domestic raw materials, as well as rising prices for finished products, "Tamara Kasyanova, Ph.D., First Vice President of the All-Russian Public Organization" Russian Club of Financial Directors, "said.
Undoubtedly, the idea of selling at least 50% of Russian food products in each category will help to secure the sector for local producers.
In this case, they will compete with each other, not with goods that are cheaper because of subsidies from another country.
In other words, the battle for the buyer will unfold between companies operating under the same industry laws.
On the other hand, Kasyanova notes, Russian producers are not able to meet 50% of the domestic needs of their compatriots in all respects.
And in this situation, retail chains will have to "reach" the share of Russian goods up to half of the assortment.
As a result, there are growing fears that substandard goods will reach the shelves.
It is possible that foreign products with broken labels will be supplied under the guise of Russian-made products, "the expert adds.
The negative impact of quotas will be felt by large retail chains, especially those that are better off cooperating with importers.
Logically, in this scenario, foreign suppliers themselves would suffer, as demand for their products would decline.
Litvinenko does not rule out that the law on quotas for domestic goods may affect consumers as well.
The fact is that some Russian-made products may be inferior in quality to their imported counterparts, while stores will be able to inflate the prices of the latter as if they were a scarce commodity.
Economists started talking about the idea of import substitution, which had been forgotten in the early 2000s, again in February of this year, because of the relentless devaluation of the rouble.
Now, against the backdrop of difficult relations with the West, the issue of abandoning imported products is becoming even more urgent.
The law is intended to oblige retailers to take into account domestic producers when placing orders with suppliers.
Then we will go much faster and more confidently on the path of import substitution, and a system of production planning for the necessary types of products will be created in a shorter time, "Deputy Oleg Nilov says.
A quota mechanism would be particularly effective in those agricultural sectors where the potential is particularly high, such as the dairy sector, where the share of imports was 25%.
Our farmers are really able to cover the shelves of Russian stores completely.
In addition, meat production could receive a powerful boost.
As is well known, the largest share of imports remains for beef - from 30% to 35%.
It turns out that 65-70% is still accounted for by Russian products, "Kasyanova argues.
Experts are of the opinion that the introduction of quotas for domestic products will promote import substitution and may accelerate this process.
However, this initiative by itself will not lead to import substitution, as it requires a set of measures, Litvinenko is convinced.
In any case, 50% of the goods sold under this initiative can still be imported, which means that full-fledged import substitution will not occur, but significant steps in this direction will be taken.
Moreover, it is not enough to set quotas, it is still necessary to establish domestic production in the country in order to fulfill these quotas.
These quotas will provide just such guarantees, "the expert states.
Delayed diagnosis and lack of access to optimal treatment mean ovarian cancer kills more in rural areas
Angelina Jolie and her brother James have released a video tribute to their late mother, who died of ovarian cancer in 2007.
Women living in rural Australia face a higher risk of dying from ovarian cancer than those living in cities.
Researchers analysed the medical records of more than 1100 Australian women diagnosed with ovarian cancer in 2005, finding that just 35 per cent lived five years after diagnosis.
Lead researcher Susan Jordan of the QIMR Berghofer Institute for Medical Research said those living in regional and remote areas of the state were 20 per cent more likely to die during the study than those living in urban areas.
