Researchers tracked the women's medical journey for seven years.
Dr Jordan said a woman's age at the time of diagnosis, ovarian cancer type, current illness and socioeconomic status also affected her chances of survival.
Older women and those with advanced cancer at the time of diagnosis had the lowest survival rates.
Those who lived in regional or remote areas of the state were 20 percent more likely to die during the study than those who lived in urban areas.
Although the study was not designed to determine why women living outside cities were more likely to die of ovarian cancer, Dr Jordan suggested that delayed diagnosis and lack of access to optimal treatment were possible factors.
"This disease is best treated by gynaecological oncology surgeons, and they are mostly in big cities," she said.
Despite improving telemedicine services to reduce the impact of distance, she suggested that more out-of-home services, which would allow specialists to treat women closer to home, and programs to support people receiving treatment far from home, could help.
Dr Jordan said that regardless of geographical location, the study found that long life expectancy among women with ovarian cancer was rare, highlighting the need for more effective treatment and prevention strategies.
The study, funded by Rio Tinto Ride to Conquer cancer, will be published today in the Medical Journal of Australia.
In March 2012, at the age of 33, young Gold Coast mother Elisha Neave was told she had an aggressive form of ovarian cancer.
