Inflation is out of control.
Will Russians Feel the Price Rise?
As a result of cross-sanctions between the Russian Federation and the West, inflation in Russia will accelerate and will not meet the authorities "forecasts, VTB Capital analysts are convinced.
According to experts, the delayed consequences of anti-sanctions will lead to an inflationary shock in the first quarter of 2015, writes RBC Daily.
According to the Ministry of Economic Development's latest forecast, inflation will be 6.5-7.5% in 2014, and 6.5% next year or less.
However, according to Kommersant newspaper, this week the Ministry of Economic Development is expected to make "small but fundamental" corrections to the macroeconomic forecast until 2017.
According to the publication, the agency may lower the inflation estimate for 2015, which will eliminate the expected zero growth in household incomes.
The forecast assumed that Russia's food sanctions would last for a year - until August 2015.
How, in such a situation, could inflation have been expected to be so high?
The current situation presupposes a one-time shock, but the downward trend of inflation will not change, "stated the newspaper's source in the Ministry of Finance.
Economists from VTB Capital do not share the expectations of the government's financial and economic bloc regarding inflation and forecast an 8% rise in prices in 2014.
The main effect of the food bans will come together with the possible introduction of a sales tax in the regions of the Russian Federation in 2015, experts are convinced.
The inflation peak of 9% will fall in February, after which the annual rate of price growth will decline, experts believe.
By the way, last week Rosstat summed up the first inflation results after the Russian Federation introduced "tidy sanctions."
I polled the experts and ascertained their inflation expectations.
Artem Deev, Head of Analytical Department, AForex:
Price increases are already being observed in major product segments.
Moreover, when socially important products became more expensive, the government was forced to put in place measures to monitor price stability systematically, in order to prevent the risk of unwarranted price increases in the short term.
Suppliers and retailers already report to regulators on a daily basis, so that authorities know exactly who is triggering price increases, when, and for what reason.
The key factors behind the rise in the consumer price index continue to be the colossal rate of capital outflows, the excessive refinancing of the banking sector by the Russian mega-regulator, domestic conversion due to the flight of the population into foreign currency, and the embargo on the import of foodstuffs from countries that have joined the sanctions against Russia.
If inflationary pressures had remained under control, the cost of a basket of minimum products would not have jumped by 12% in the quarter alone.
The ban on the import of foodstuffs triggered a supply shock on the domestic market and led to an entirely logical increase in the final cost.
As we are currently unable to fully launch the import substitution mechanism, as well as to increase the self-sufficiency of the Russian market at the expense of domestic production, retaliatory sanctions will continue to carry the risks of an inflationary component.
Add to that the fiscal reasons associated with a lack of confidence in the national currency and a worsening growth outlook, and inflation could well exceed 8% by the end of this year.
Alexander Razuvaev, Director of the Analytical Department of Alpari
In the 1990 "s, inflation sometimes reached 20-30% per month, and at zero it was also higher than the current level, which was then offset by rapid economic growth.
I think that by the end of the year, inflation will amount to 8-8.5%.
Platon Maguta, Asset Manager, Maguta Foundation Management Company
The external factor associated with the sanctions against Russia has so far been successfully contained, but if there is a further increase in pressure, primarily on the financial sector, it could lead to certain difficulties and increase the inflation expectations of the population, which are usually manifested in purchases of cash currency in order to secure their savings.
One can assume that the government, the Central Bank of the Russian Federation, and the Ministry of Finance will try to mitigate the smooth depreciation of the ruble, both by market methods and state regulation.
But price growth traditionally begins after the summer lull and may become more pronounced this autumn.
The target rate of 7.5% for consumer inflation in Russia is likely to survive, as the Russian Federation still has financial savings.
Gardening centers mourn decline in homeownership
Such a drop, driven by an exceptional fall in the number of homeowners under 35, could see gardening centres lose tens of millions of pounds a year as today's young consumers reach the "mainstream gardening age," according to the HTA study reported by the Financial Times.
According to the report, renters spend an average of 55 per cent of what homeowners spend on gardening.
It cites the increase in the number of people living in highly urbanized areas without gardens, the popularity of asphalting courtyards in front of homes for parking, and the shrinking size of the garden as other factors threatening the industry, which has an estimated annual sales of £5 billion.
Greater London, where the number of homeowners has fallen from 61 per cent to 43 per cent in six years, has the lowest spending per household on gardening goods in the UK.
The HTA and the Royal Horticultural Society said renting accommodation and a lack of garden space did not mean people could not grow plants.
Guy Barter, chief horticultural adviser at the RHS, said: "Growing plants in containers, for example, is particularly popular with renters who can transport plants with them when they move."
The HTA report defined the period between 1997 and 2005 as the "golden age" of horticultural retailing as a result of rising home ownership and economic prosperity from the late 1980s to the mid-1990s.
It also predicts that the market will improve this year thanks to better weather after adverse conditions in March and April last year.
