It turned out that two of the fund's three deputy executive directors had also been quietly replaced on Friday.
Deputy Executive Director Tatiana Angelova, who was previously in charge of state aid and the SAPARD program, has been released, reports BGNES, with reference to the newspaper Trud.
I did not attend the Board of Governors of the Fund because, by law, we are not members of the Board of Governors, but I was later informed that I had been released.
I cannot say why my dismissal is not reported on the foundation's website.
I'm on vacation.
I hope I will find out more on Monday, "Angelova told the publication.
She will be replaced by Ivanka Bagdatova, who was until now the head of "Investment Credit" at the central fund at "Agriculture" in Sofia.
Deputy Executive Director Nikolai Dachev was also released.
Until then, he was responsible for direct subsidies for fields paid by the EU.
In his place will be appointed Zhivko Zhivkov, who was the head of the Regional Directorate of the Agriculture Fund in the city of Veliko Tarnovo until January 2014.
Only Deputy Head of the Foundation, Atije Aliyeva-Veli, retained her post.
It is currently responsible for the Rural Development Programme.
The official reasons for all the changes in the agency are not mentioned.
Turkey summons US diplomat over spying report
Turkey's foreign ministry has summoned the country's most senior American diplomat to explain a report on American and British espionage in Turkey.
Deputy Prime Minister Bulent said the American chargé d'affaires and Turkish officials discussed the report on Monday.
German magazine Der Spiegel and the online magazine The Intercept reported that documents provided by former US National Security Agency analyst Edward Snowden show that Turkey was a priority intelligence target for US and British intelligence services.
According to Turkish news agencies, Turkish President Recep Tayyip Erdoğan downplayed the importance of the report, saying that all major countries were spying on each other.
Earlier reports that Germany's main intelligence agency had also targeted Ankara provoked a more angry response from the Turkish government.
China's biggest companies unite against Alibaba
Chinese companies, including China's largest commercial real estate developer Dalian Wanda Group and Internet giants Tencent Holdings (social media, messenger, etc.) and Baidu (China's largest search engine), are creating a company that will compete in the online trading market with Alibaba.
But catching up with the miracle of the Chinese Internet, which has left even its US rivals, eBay and Amazon.com, behind, will not be easy.
Union of the largest
The companies plan to invest 5 billion yuan ($814 million) in the joint venture, 70% of which will belong to Wanda and 15% to each of the Internet companies, the Wanda Group said in a statement.
It is planned to register the firm in Hong Kong.
The joint venture will combine Baidu's search services with the popular social platform WeChat (the largest social network in China, with about 438 million users), Tencent, and Wanda's infrastructure.
In addition to a network of 40 luxury hotels, the Wanda Group operates at least 49 commercial real estate properties throughout China and 40 shopping malls.
Last year, the company invested 50 billion yuan (more than $8 billion) in the construction of a movie studio and theme park in Qingdao, a city in eastern China on the banks of the Yellow Sea.
It is expected that the project will attract more than 1 million visitors annually and generate a profit of $960 million.
In addition, Wanda owns the American cinema chain AMC Entertainment Holdings, making the company the largest movie theater operator in the world.
By 2015, Wanda plans to equip all of its shopping malls, hotels, and entertainment venues with e-commerce services, which will be developed by rival Alibaba.
According to Dong Tse, who will head the new company, the merger will enable Wanda to increase the number of users of its e-commerce services from the current 40 million to 100 million by next year.
The new platform should become the world's largest online-to-offline platform, notes Dong Tse.
The essence of online-to-offline (O2O) commerce is to attract online shoppers to go to regular offline stores or buy other traditional services.
A classic example of O2O are coupon services like Groupon or Vigoda.ru.
"O2O is the biggest pie in online commerce," said Wanda CEO Wang Jianlin (quoted by Bloomberg).
"Right now, there is no real O2O site in China, and in this situation, the odds are roughly equal for everyone," he said.
China's e-commerce market is the world's largest, and McKinsey & Co estimates that its volume will more than triple by 2015 compared to 2011, to $395 billion.
The number of Chinese Internet users has grown to 632 million, according to official statistics cited by Bloomberg: this is more than the population of any country in the world, with the exception of India.
And, according to projections, that number could rise to 850 million by 2015.
Union of the richest
Tencent CEO Ma Huateng was until recently China's richest man, but according to Bloomberg's index of millionaires, Alibaba founder Jack Ma has already overtaken him by $5.5 billion.
Jack Ma's fortune is estimated at $21.8 billion, of which $11 billion is his stake in Alibaba.
Baidu chief Robin Li now ranks third among China's richest people, while Wanda's Wang Jianlin is fourth.
"It's very interesting to watch this battle: the three richest people are joining forces to challenge the even wealthier," Cao Lei, director of the China E-Commerce Research Center in Hangzhou, told Bloomberg.
But he believes the new company is unlikely to compete seriously with Alibaba once it is established: "Rome cannot be built overnight."
That it is not easy to compete not only with Alibaba, but also with the established leaders of global e-commerce, is evidenced by the report released yesterday on Alibaba's financial results for the last quarter.
Alibaba is often described as somewhere between eBay and Amazon.com, but from April to June the Chinese company earned more than both of its US competitors combined.
Alibaba's net profit for the period is almost double that of its competitors combined - it nearly tripled year-on-year to $1.99 billion.
"Alibaba still has huge potential to generate money, thanks largely to its mobile apps," an analyst from Hong Kong's Arete Research Service told Bloomberg.
According to Alibaba's updated prospectus on the website of the US Securities and Exchange Commission, the number of active mobile users of the company's services in July was 188 million, which is significantly higher than the figure in March (163 million people).
At the same time, 32.8% of all Alibaba transactions in the last quarter were on mobile devices.
Alibaba is yet to reveal the value of its shares ahead of the IPO.
According to the average estimate of 11 analysts surveyed by Bloomberg, the company could be valued at $187 billion after the share sale.
According to Bloomberg sources, Alibaba's debut on the New York Stock Exchange (NYSE) could take place as early as September 16.
The company's road-show preceding this event will start on September 3.
Alibaba's IPO is expected to be the largest in the history of the NYSE and will allow the company to raise about $20 billion.
Until now, the record volume of funds raised on US exchanges belonged to the payment system Visa, which in 2008 conducted an initial public offering of its shares, earning $17.9 billion.
At least half of the food products in retail chains should be of Russian origin, according to State Duma deputies.
They have drafted a bill to that effect.
The issue is the introduction of amendments to Article 8 of the Federal Law "On the Fundamentals of State Regulation of Trade Activities in the Russian Federation" and to the Tax Code.
The aim of the document is to introduce protective measures against Russian food producers.
An important clarification, according to the bill, is that no less than 50 percent of domestically produced products in stores should be for each type of product.
However, the document will take into account that there are goods that are not produced in Russia, for example, vegetables and fruits in winter, so a "discount" will be made for them to avoid possible discomfort for buyers.
At the same time, the draft law also amends the Tax Code of the Russian Federation, which establishes a reduced VAT rate of 10% for the sale of all foodstuffs whose country of origin is Russia, Izvestia newspaper reports.
On August 27, a draft law on amendments to the Federal Law "On retail markets" was submitted to the lower house of parliament, which proposes to revive farmers "markets in Russia, where small producers can sell their products.
Magaluf police chief charged with corruption
The plaintiffs presented evidence of extortion by police and Calvia municipal officials to Mallorca's public prosecutor's office on Friday.
The police chief of Calvia on the resort island of Mallorca has been arrested following allegations of corruption by businessmen and bar owners at Magaluf's notorious binge drinking centre.
Chief Inspector José Antonio Navarro has been remanded in custody following corruption charges brought against him by several businessmen from Punta Ballena, the street where most of Magaluf's bars and nightclubs are located.
According to the online daily Mallorca Diario, the plaintiffs presented evidence of extortion by police and Calvia municipal officials to Mallorca's anti-corruption prosecutor's office on Friday.
Two other local police officers have been arrested by Spanish National Guard officers on corruption charges and will be questioned by a judge along with Navarro.
Spanish daily ABC reported that disgruntled nightclub owners say government protectionism is seriously affecting their businesses.
"It's no longer about making money, it's about surviving," one businessman told the court.
Our livelihoods must not be put at risk.
We have nothing to lose.
Magaluf made international headlines this summer after a popular YouTube video showed an 18-year-old British holidaymaker groping 24 men during a bar crawl.
The island's authorities have since been trying to stop drunken hooliganism among Magaluf holidaymakers by minimising the number of notorious alcohol runs in bars.
In addition, the Playhouse club where the mint incident occurred was forced to close for a year, while Playhouse and the Carnage bar race organisers were jointly fined €55,000 ($73,000).
The tourist resort of Magaluf, mainly popular with young British holidaymakers, has also been the scene of numerous drunken accidents linked to the craze known as "balcony jumping," in which people jump from one balcony to another or from a balcony into a hotel pool.
First day of spring marked by wet and windy conditions affecting flights at Adelaide Airport
Spring has brought a cold snap to southern South Australia, bringing torrential rain and strong winds that have affected flights at Adelaide Airport.
Another 5mm of rain fell on the city by 9pm, following the 6.6mm that fell overnight on Sunday.
The latest rain was preceded by a couple of short downpours with gusty winds, including a thunderstorm that began just before 8pm and dumped almost 4mm in about 10 minutes.
After winter delivered an early dose of spring last week, temperatures fell again on Monday to a high of just 15.8C in the city.
The squally conditions are believed to have contributed to the delay of the Virgin Airlines flight from Melbourne to Adelaide.
The plane was scheduled to land just after 7: 30 p.m., but hit a zone of wind shear - a sudden change in wind speed or direction at a short distance - and was forced to gain altitude.
Wind gusts reached 50km / h on the ground at Adelaide Airport at the time.
Flight data showed the plane had to gain altitude on its second landing, and the plane eventually landed around 8: 40 p.m.
The delay caused further delays to several other flights, including an Emirates flight from Dubai and a Qantas flight from Sydney.
A maximum of 16C is forecast for Adelaide on Tuesday, with a chance of one or two showers.
Calculation of estimates of construction projects in the Russian Federation will take place in a new way
The Federal Antimonopoly Service takes special control over issues of pricing, regulation of the construction industry, as well as problems of connection to networks.
An expert council on the development of competition in the construction sector has been established under the FAS.
At his meeting, the Head of the Department for Control of Housing, Construction and Natural Resources of the FAS, Vadim Solovyev, stated that "today's calculation of the budget for construction projects is absolutely unclear."
The regulatory framework makes pricing opaque and may lead to an unreasonable construction price, according to the FAS.
And they suggest that the cost of construction of state-owned facilities at the design stage should be determined on the basis of market prices of design solutions, instead of the estimated norms and unit rates for technological operations currently applied.
These proposals have been included in the "road map" and are currently under consideration by the Ministry of Construction.
"The replacement of traditional cost estimates in construction with calculations of structural elements should lead to less corruption in the industry," Vadim Solovyev explained to RGB.
After all, now every bolt and nut is counted in the estimate, and it is not always possible to check everything, so sometimes unscrupulous construction companies can bury "whole tractors" in the documentation.
The Ministry of Construction agrees with the FAS.
"The first achievements on the transition to the calculation of the cost of structural elements are already in place: methodologies have been developed for calculating the prices for structural solutions and making estimates according to these indicators," Elena Zhukova, Head of the Department of Urban Planning and Architecture of the Ministry of Construction, told RGB.
Road construction has been chosen as a pilot project.
However, experts believe that the problem is much more serious.
As Anatoly Demyanko, Head of the Profi-Invest construction company, told RGB, the estimated norms have been out of date for a long time, but no other mechanism has yet been offered to business.
"As for the proposed calculations on structural elements, in practice it is difficult to realize, because the construction of buildings often uses completely different technologies," he believes.
It is no secret that the construction market is developing largely thanks to government contracts.
According to Ekaterina Lezina, Chairman of the Board of the NGO Expert Community of Government Procurement Professionals, today the state is the most solvent customer.
Vladimir Malakhov, Deputy Director for Engineering at the branch capital construction center of Rosatom, drew attention to the fact that today the market is conditionally divided into companies that have access to a portfolio of contracts, and companies that possess monopoly competencies and do not allow competitors to enter this field.
He believes that the creation of a transparent market is possible only if access to contracts is protected as much as possible from someone else's controlling influence.
At the Expert Council, it was proposed to form a system of state procurement in such a way that the same contractor is not entitled to receive more than one contract worth more than 1 billion roubles or several contracts worth more than 1 billion roubles.
The Ministry of Construction believes that this approach should be evaluated in terms of its impact on business, as well as the effectiveness of construction management.
As Elena Zhukova explained, in this case, it will be necessary to endow the client with the functions of general contractor, which will lead to an increase in the number of staff of the client and budgetary expenditures for its maintenance.
At the same time, the customer's specialists will have to possess the knowledge to assess the quality of the work performed by contractors, as well as its safety.
Often, such a breakdown will have to determine who will be responsible for the safety of the facility as a whole.
In addition, this approach may lead to an outflow of highly qualified participants in public procurement due to a lack of interest in receiving a state order for an incomplete amount of work and a small contract amount.
Alexander Evstashenkov, Deputy Head of the Expert-Consulting Center of the Procurement Institute, believes that now the procedure of state procurement has turned into a business game for the attention of the contractor.
And he gave an example: "when filling out an application, a participant should indicate" specific indicators "without the words:" or equivalent, "" should be, "" from, "" more than, "" less than, "" analogue, "" or, "" type, "" similar type, "" not lower than, "" lower than, "" higher than, "" may, "may have," may be, "" earlier than, "" not earlier than, "not higher than," not permitted, "etc.
Thus, customers often abuse their right to set requirements for the content of an application submitted by contracting organizations.
Another problem with FZ 44, according to Evstashenkov, was the need to assess the quality of work through the participant's "paper" proposal at the application submission stage.
Considering the participant's application, it is really possible to assess only the qualifications of the contractor, but not the quality of work that has not even begun to be performed, the expert believes.
The quality of work can be assessed only when it is accepted.
At the Expert Council, it was also proposed to shift marginal income from the upper to the lower echelon in order to eliminate interim contractors.
Chairman of the Expert Council, State Secretary, Deputy Head of the FAS Andrei Tsarikovsky believes that this should not be done, as the general contractor should be responsible for the order.
Otherwise it will turn out, as in Arkady Raikin's famous reprise of "The Atelier": "Are there any claims to the buttons?"
Israeli Children Return to School After Gaza War
Thousands of Israeli children in territories near Gaza returned to school on Monday after spending the summer in bomb shelters when rockets and mortars rained down on their settlements during the 50-day war between Israel and Hamas, while schools in Gaza remained closed as the territory recovered from the fighting.
The start of school brought joy and excitement to rocket-hit settlements in southern Israel, but traces of the fighting remained fresh.
In the southern city of Ashdod, staff at the Pashosh kindergarten, which was hit by a rocket, removed shrapnel marks from walls and slides before the students arrived.
"We are a little scared, but we are excited about the future," said Ronit Bart, a resident of Kibbutz Saad and an English teacher at his school.
Many children in our area really need to get back to a normal life.
Her 11-year-old daughter, Shani Bart, said suddenly starting school again was "a bit weird."
"It was a difficult time and we didn't leave our houses at all," she said.
President Reuven Rivlin visited a kibbutz near the Gaza border to express his support.
Before the cease-fire ended the war last week, thousands of residents of border settlements like Sa'ad stayed indoors or fled their homes to safer areas further away from Gaza to escape rocket and mortar fire.
Many residents of Nahal Oz, the settlement near the Gaza border where a 4-year-old boy was killed by a Palestinian mortar shell, are hesitant to return.
The Education Ministry said about a dozen families had still not returned.
Their children were sent to other schools for the time being.
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu visited a school in Sderot, a town on the Gaza border that has struggled under Palestinian fire.
He advised the children to study hard and said: "We will do everything possible to give you the knowledge and to ensure your safety."
Israel and Hamas agreed to an indefinite truce last Tuesday.
The ceasefire immediately ended the fighting, but key issues remained unresolved, such as Hamas's demand for the lifting of the Egyptian-Israeli blockade of Gaza and the reopening of Gaza's airports and seaports.
Israel wants Hamas to lay down its arms and return the bodies of two Israeli soldiers killed in the war.
A new round of proximity talks is expected to begin later this month in Egypt.
The war has killed more than 2,100 Palestinians, three-quarters of them civilians, and at least 494 children, according to estimates by the Palestinian side and the UN.
Israel disputes these figures and claims that at least half of those killed were militants; however, it has not provided substantial evidence to support this claim.
On the Israeli side, 66 soldiers and six civilians, including one Thai worker, were killed.
During the fighting, Hamas and other Gaza militants fired 4,591 rockets and mortars at Israeli cities, mostly in the south of the country.
The Israeli army, meanwhile, has carried out more than 5,000 air and other attacks.
Israeli attacks damaged and destroyed thousands of homes in the Gaza Strip, and an estimated 250,000 people took refuge in more than 100 schools, which were converted into shelters.
With tens of thousands still in shelters and fighting continuing, education officials last week postponed the start of the school year.
"I hope that the school will open soon so that we can complete our education like the children of the world and Jewish children," said Mohammad Amara, a 13-year-old boy who now lives in a Gaza school.
According to a popular measure, property prices posted their biggest winter increase in seven years.
The RP Data CoreLogic Hedonic home value index for Australian capital city house prices rose 1.1 per cent in August, RP data reported on Monday.
That increase led to a combined increase of 4.2 percent for June, July, and August, the largest increase in the winter months since 2007.
Annual price growth was 10.9 per cent, more than double the increase in the 12 months to August 2013, but the increase was not spread evenly across the country.
RP Data research director Tim Lawless said Sydney and Melbourne had a two-tier market.
Figures from RP Data show Sydney house prices have risen 16.1 per cent in the past year, while Melbourne has risen 11.7 per cent.
The next strongest markets were Adelaide, Brisbane and Darwin, where prices rose by an average of five to six per cent.
At the other end of the scale was Canberra, which experienced government spending cuts, with prices rising by just 1.4 per cent for the year.
Mr Lawless said that now that spring had begun, there would be an increase in the number of properties for sale over the next few months, which would be a "real test" for the market.
"Given the current high auction rate, the overall high sale rate and the current low interest rate environment, it is likely that house prices will rise further over the next three months," he said.
How people live in the oldest house in Ufa
In the former house of gold producers and miners Evdokim and his son Ivan Demidov at 57 / 1 October Revolution Street (formerly Bolshaya Kazanskaya) there are 18 apartments.
The 18th century house has hardly changed since it was built, except for its decay.
Strangers come here as if on a tour, and the residents suffer more than they rejoice from their privilege - the right to live in the oldest Ufa house, the walls of which remember the commander Aleksandr Suvorov.
The date of construction of the house is inaccurate, historians point to two dates - 1730 and 1737.
But in any case, it turns out that the building is almost 300 years old.
The old courtyard, the always open door, the creaky staircase.
The doors to the apartments are located close to each other, the walls have cracked, and the street can be seen in the gaps from the exposed plaster.
Everything seems to be keeping to its word.
And the locals say: "You don't think so, that's the way it is."
Living in an 18th century wooden house is very difficult, says Tatiana Lukyanova, a resident of Apartment No. 3.
The object is on state conservation, but no money is allocated for its maintenance for decades, and we feel like museum exhibits that the authorities have simply forgotten.
The last renovation was 40 years ago.
The walls are still poorly maintained, but the entire foundation is rotten.
Many residents still go outside to use the toilet and wash themselves once a week in the public bath.
How can one be satisfied in such conditions?!
The road runs right under the windows, there is not even a pedestrian zone.
Tatiana pulls back the curtain.
Now you can see what was only audible before: a stream of cars rumbling through the windows.
You see, the glass shakes constantly, we can't open the windows, and we're used to the noise.
One gets used to everything, to the good and the bad.
Our apartment is still exemplary, thanks to my husband, his hands are golden.
Especially, we have two rooms, we live together with our son.
Conditions are much worse for other families, with ceilings just over a metre and a half high on the second floor.
For contrast, Tatiana suggests visiting a neighbor from Apartment No. 6, Lyudmila Starostina.
A pleasant hospitable woman offers a cup of coffee on the doorstep and says with a sad smile:
We have a one-room apartment, 14.5 m ² for four people, so we live that way: my husband and I have a daughter and a granddaughter.
I have been here since I was born, there has never been any other living space, "Lyudmila looks around the room: a mezzanine, two sofas with the letter" d, "one of which is occupied by her granddaughter with a laptop.
Very cramped and differs little from the usual domestic interior: only the ceilings are beautiful, "historical."
But the ceiling is leaking regularly: the plumbing system is nowhere to be seen.
Lyudmila speaks of her apartment in a mundane and surprising way at the same time, like an Italian whose house stands on Roman ruins.
That is, it brings together the very old and the recent, the everyday and the legendary:
The plumbing was installed about 40 years ago during the last renovation.
At the same time, they made us a small kitchen in the back room and a toilet from a former closet.
We live just where Demidov and his family lived, and servants lived on the second floor.
Our apartment is not privatized, and why?
The Ufa Real Estate Centre says that privatization does not matter.
Still, we will get only a one-room apartment, we cannot claim for more.
It was already four months ago that they promised to resettle us, but they didn't go further than that.
I'm not used to complaining and I won't.
In this apartment (room!) a whole dynasty lived: my grandparents, my mum and dad, my husband and I, and my daughter and granddaughter.
Everything happened during that time.
For example, hefty rats ran around the kitchen.
Look at the walls of the outbuilding, they are a metre thick!
The solution is said to have been mixed with eggs, which is why it holds for so long.
The house has been built thoroughly, thanks to the Demidovs!
Perhaps that is why no one has been killed so far by a collapsed ceiling or pile.
Only the building is still slowly dying before our eyes: the boards and logs of the house are rotting, the floors have repeatedly collapsed, we poured cement, but all to no avail - the mortar goes into the ground like a well.
They say so - there is a secret manhole under our room and a route to the Belaya River, which was specially made by the old believers who once lived here, so that they could take refuge from danger, in case of what.
They were persecuted.
Lyudmila Starostina tells how some historian came to them and begged them to let him start excavations in the apartment.
And then he persuaded them to give him a place to live in exchange for his one-room apartment on Oktyabrya Avenue.
Lyudmila refused the historian:
Where do the four of us go from here?
Here, there is even a tiny hope that they will provide more spacious housing.
If we had agreed to the exchange, we would not have won anything.
However, the Starostin family did not win anything.
Lyudmila's biggest dream is to be resettled and her daughter and 16-year-old granddaughter given a separate room.
That is, a two-room apartment was allocated for two families instead of the not-so-grand ruins in which two generations now live.
Cute, petite girl Olesya Karsakova from Apartments 11 and 12 shows the second floor of the house.
There, in two cramped rooms with a total area of 23 m ², called apartments, lives her extended family.
There are seven of us, two of us children.
You can see for yourself what the conditions are.
The plaster falls off in pieces, as do the window frames, and there are holes in the walls in the kitchen and in the rooms.
The tap water is only cold all year round.
Walking through the apartments of the oldest house in Ufa, one can see that the Lavrentyev couple from Apartment No. 4 were the lucky ones.
They occupy the most spacious rooms on the ground floor.
You are right, there is plenty of space!
The room is 75 square meters, three people are registered.
We live in the very rooms where Suvorov, according to legend, stayed during his stay in Ufa, says the head of the family, Alexander Dmitrievich Lavrentyev.
The ceilings are high and spacious.
One thing is bad - everything around is cracking at the seams, falling apart, collapsing.
Neighbors, probably, have already told!
We suffer the most with the floors: the wooden planks have rotted, the ground has literally gone from under our feet.
I put up supports, wedges; there is nothing in the room, and in another room we walk like we swing, everything is so shaky.
Alexander Dmitrievich can tell more about the house of the merchant Evdokim Demidov than any tour guide.
He treats the gold miner as if he were his own, speaks of him with admiration.
Indeed, his personality was extraordinary: the owner of the Kaginsky and Uzyansky plants built houses, cast cannons and bells, and kept the Ural mines.
The heirs of merchant real estate are proud of their ancestors, but they no longer want to live under the same roof as history.
I moved here as a child, in the 1940s, says Aleksandr Dmitrievich.
Back then, there were wooden carriage houses, stables and guard booths around, which were later demolished.
In 1968, they wanted to clean up our house, but something got in the way...
History repeated itself in 2014: again lured by new housing.
We, as a team, collected all the documents, ran through the necessary authorities, and suddenly learned that the move to the apartments was postponed to 2015 or 2016.
Something we don't believe in anymore...
Two years ago, Lavrentyev went to the Ministry of Culture of the Republic of Bashkortostan to find out about the fate of the house.
Officials did not accept the occupant.
Sent from one table to another, and then, as if in mockery, given a piece of paper without a signature and stamp: "The Ministry of Culture does not object to the resettlement of residents."
I even have a feeling that our house has not been in the city plan for a long time, because first it was number 57, then it became 57 A, and now it is 57 / 1.
As if it had already been demolished in the 1970s.
Russian Planet appealed to Vladimir Barabash, Head of the Information and Analytical Work Sector of the Land Resources Department of Ufa.
The house at 57 / 1 October Revolution Street is included in the program of resettlement of dilapidated housing.
I cannot be held responsible for the actions of the officials of the 1970s, but I know that at that time there was a plan to demolish all the old houses, despite their historical significance.
Fortunately, this did not happen, and the decision of the modern authorities - to restore all the ancient buildings along October Revolution Street that are of architectural value - is being successfully implemented.
In the near future, it is planned to resettle the residents in new apartments.
According to Barabash, the restoration of Demidov's House will be carried out by Italian specialists who participated in the restoration of buildings in Venice.
Now an architectural biennale is taking place in Italy, and the project "Staraya Ufa" is represented there, among others.
I hope that by 2016 the whole former Stara Kazanskaya Street will have been restored, says the official.
The houses will get a proper look, corresponding to what they used to be, three centuries ago.
Demidov's House is likely to become a museum open to all comers.
In addition, a decision has been made at the government level to make the street pedestrian on weekends.
On weekdays, unfortunately, it will not work, there is too much traffic in the city.
Vladimir Barabash promises to resettle people from the future museum in 2015.
However, they are unlikely to be happy: their new apartments will be the same size as the current ones.
Only from a different era.
A forest fire has started in Primorye due to a thunderstorm
A dry thunderstorm caused a forest fire in the Okhotsky precinct forest district in the Pozharsky district of Primorsky Krai.
At the site of the fire, a build-up of forces and assets is underway.
According to information from the leadership of the Primorskaya Air Base, the conditions created at the site of the fire require the involvement of aviation forces.
Vasily Medvedev, Deputy Head of the airbase:
The fire, which arose in difficult terrain, was detected by an observer pilot on board an AN-2 patrol aircraft on an area of 3 hectares.
Wood residues are burning on the old fire.
Severe overcrowding in the territory and a slope of more than 45 degrees, as well as the lack of landing sites suitable for fire fighters, create considerable difficulties in extinguishing the fires.
An MI-8 helicopter is needed.
The airbase's Mi-2 helicopter and An-2 fixed-wing aircraft have made the delivery of forces very difficult.
After the fire was detected, 4 parachutists-firefighters were promptly dropped off at the place of extinguishing the fire.
The main task of the specialists is to extinguish the fire and prepare the site for the delivery of additional firefighting forces and means.
In the vicinity of lunch, an additional 3 paratroopers were delivered by helicopter to the area of the village of Okhotichy.
As soon as the helicopter landing site in the area of the fire is ready, specialists will be deployed to the place of extinguishing, according to the website of the Primorsky Krai administration.
Lenny Henry: My father never hugged me.
Never said, "I love you"
Henry was one of seven children born to Jamaican immigrants in Dudley in the Midlands in 1958.
His father, who died when Henry was 19, worked in a factory and their relationship was limited.
Henry is rehearsing a comedy, Rudy's Rare Records, which is partly based on imaginary conversations with his father and grew out of a Radio 4 series.
The soundtrack is a mix of reggae and rap, and the melodies are cheerful.
But Henry had to work his way through some difficult childhood memories.
Since his mother's death, there has been "a lot" of treatment, and Henry often reflects on his relationship with his father.
It was very inaccessible.
You never saw his face, you just heard his voice: "Stop making noise.
Get behind your sister.
