4 Tips for Getting Better Underwater Photos and Videos
If you want to photograph or video underwater, there are a number of options.
The cheapest option is a waterproof soapbox, such as the Nikon Coolpix AW120, or an action camera, such as the GoPro Hero3 + Silver Edition, both of which sell for around $300.
I took these pictures at a family party with a few cameras, all for about $350.
No matter what equipment you use, a few rules must be followed in order to achieve the best results.
Re-check your equipment.
Even if you have a waterproof camera, make sure the camera's battery and other compartments are tightly closed.
Also, set up your camera for the type of photos or videos you're shooting.
Some cameras and camcorders have shooting modes or object types that optimize exposure for darkened underwater conditions.
And before you jump into the water, figure out how deep your equipment can sink.
Some cameras are designed for only 5 feet, others for 50 or 60 feet.
Check out our Buyer's Guide and digital camera ratings for both conventional and waterproof models.
Shoot a few shots - because many of them won't work out.
Soap cameras have LCDs to help you compose your shots, whereas action cameras don't usually have them.
Even if you have LCD, it will be difficult to see underwater, and the layout of the frame will be a random process.
So take a few shots.
Also, if your camera has a serial mode that shoots multiple frames with slightly different exposure settings, use it.
Stay close to the surface.
The amount of light decreases significantly the deeper you dive underwater.
If possible, stay close to the surface when you shoot in a pool, river or ocean.
It will also allow you to convey more color in photos; the deeper you go, the less color you will see.
Get closer to the subjects you're shooting.
This is great advice for shooting on land, but it is even more important underwater because of the dim light conditions.
Particularly important if you shoot with an action camera: This equipment often has a fixed, wide-angle lens, which means that you will have to get closer to your subjects if you want to fill the frame.
