Andrew Lawson was the sort of man whose personality might shake things up, even in an organisation as gigantic as the NHS.
A consultant anaesthetist, he devoted his career to relieving patients of both the pain of illness and the agony of treatment.
Among those who approached him, his wife recalls, was an MI6 officer who had to live with the devastating consequences of torture.
Lawson understood that as long as doctors are preoccupied with diagnoses and illnesses, those being treated are primarily concerned with something else entirely: pain.
One day in 2007, however, he was the one who began to suffer.
"I didn't feel normal," he wrote in May last year.
It was hard for me to find strength in myself.
Struggling with flu-like symptoms, he found himself angrily rebuking his wife, Juliet.
"I want things to happen faster, not later," he said.
When Juliet went away on business for a week, Lawson found himself unusually and inexplicably upset.
Something was wrong.
He asked a colleague for a chest X-ray.
Just two weeks earlier, he had been skiing in the French Alps.
The results of the X-ray came.
It was mesothelioma, an incurable cancer that affects the pleura, or lining of the lungs.
For most cancers, it is difficult to know the exact cause.
Although some smokers get lung cancer, for example, not all lung cancer patients have smoked.
But mesothelioma is different.
In almost all cases, the cause is exposure to asbestos, a fibrous building material once called a "miracle," but now known to be deadly.
For most of us, mesothelioma is a disease that can be overlooked.
Asbestos, after all, is a thing of the past.
The most dangerous type of asbestos has not been used in the UK since the 1960s, when a voluntary industrial ban came into force.
Even when it was used, only people from specific industries worked closely with it: pipe fitters, builders, carpenters, and dock workers, for example.
An industrial toxin from another era, it hardly seems a cause for concern today.
But such calm is a fallacy.
Britain, it turns out, is now at the peak of a mesothelioma epidemic.
Mesothelioma kills more people here than in any other country on the planet.
With an annual death toll of around 2,500, more than twice as many people die from the disease as from car accidents.
Annual mesothelioma deaths since 1980 and projected future deaths in the UK
The reason we are feeling its deadly effects now is that, although the use of asbestos has been illegal for years (all types of asbestos were eventually banned by law in 1999), mesothelioma usually takes decades to develop.
And the scourge of mesothelioma is not limited to veterans of industrial construction.
Asbestos has been, and in many cases remains, embedded in the homes where we live, the offices where we work, the schools where we study, and the shops where we shop.
As a result, mesothelioma pays no attention to class, wealth, occupation, or age.
The bastions of privilege, from trendy London department stores to private schools, have proved no salvation.
The Houses of Parliament are riddled with asbestos.
Even the hospitals that are meant to treat us have turned out to be reservoirs of this deadly carcinogen.
Andrew Lawson was not old.
He was not a pipe fitter.
In fact, he had to think about where he might have come into contact with asbestos.
Then he made up his mind.
"It seems there may have been a lot of asbestos in the tunnels at Guy's Hospital where I spent six years as a trainee," he wrote.
Everyone - students, nurses, doctors, and porters - used the tunnels.
I wonder how many of my peers will get the same disease?
It was a question to which, unfortunately, he could give a partial answer.
"Of the four doctors who trained at Guy's Hospital and subsequently developed mesothelioma over the past five years," he wrote in a 2010 letter, "I am the only one who survived."
How many of us will get the disease?
Andrew Lawson was diagnosed with mesothelioma when he was 48.
He was 55 when he died on February 17 this year.
To live so long is unusual.
Fifty percent of mesothelioma patients die 8 months after diagnosis.
It is always deadly.
So now we can only repeat Lawson's question: "How many of us will get the same disease?"
According to the UK's leading expert on mesothelioma, Professor Julian Pito, it is most likely that between 1970 and 2050, when the asbestos epidemic in the UK is due to end, some 90,000 people will die.
Most now have no idea that they will die this way.
Asbestos mine in Quebec, Canada Alamy
A quick look at the reports from the courtrooms, where victims often turn for compensation, shows how far mesothelioma's scourge has spread.
This June, for example, Marks & Spencer admitted to inadvertently exposing Janice Allen to asbestos.
She worked at the chain for nine years, from 1978 to 1987, running clothing departments at two sites, one of which was the flagship store on Oxford Street.
Mrs Allen was just 18 when she started at M & S.
