Genetic disorder is often misdiagnosed
A British woman has revealed she spent years thinking she was going to die after being misdiagnosed.
Karin Rogers spent most of her teenage years thinking she had only a few years to live after being diagnosed with another disease.
In fact, she had Charcot-Marie-Tut's disease (CMT) - a group of inherited disorders that cause nerve damage outside the brain and spine.
Charity CMT UK said misdiagnosis is a common problem among people with CMT because so little is known about the condition.
Around 23,000 people in the UK are thought to have CMT, which can cause motor symptoms such as muscle weakness, insecure gait and squeezed toes.
Sufferers may experience numbness or pain, and the condition goes untreated and progresses, meaning symptoms intensify over time.
When Rogers was 13, she thought she was suffering from Friedreich's ataxia (AF), a condition for which the prognosis was very poor.
Rogers thought she would be wheelchair bound by the time she was 18 and die before she turned 30.
The mother-of-two, now 51, said: 'As a child I knew I couldn't do what others did.
I fell every day and it took me longer to do everything.
I could never roller-skate or skateboard with other kids, and I was bullied a lot at school because of the way I walked and ran.
Rodgers said that when she was 13, after several surgeries to release her Achilles tendon and straighten her feet, she looked at her medical records when her doctor left the room and it said she had AF.
"I felt guilty because I put my nose where it shouldn't be, so I didn't tell anyone, but I went home, found information about the condition in the library and wrote to the FA Association," she said.
When I received the information in response, I was shocked and in the worst panic possible.
I thought I would be in a wheelchair at 18 and die before I was 25, and that I would gradually lose all my abilities in between.
I was going through it on my own and I planned my own funeral.
She said that by the time she turned 17, she realised her ability to walk had not deteriorated as much as she thought and asked her doctor about it.
He just stood up, hugged me and said, "My dear, I don't think you have this disease because you would have been in a wheelchair already."
I think you have something that is far less life threatening.
After several genetic tests, she was diagnosed with CMT.
"When he explained what CMT was, I thought I'd pulled out a lucky ticket," she said.
The charity CMT UK has launched CMT Awareness Month to try to raise awareness of the disease.
Tax burden on Washington-area entrepreneurs rises as economy recovers
A recovering economy means more customers, more sales, and more jobs.
It also means higher taxes.
State and local tax bills for companies across the country rose modestly last year as the economic recovery accelerated, according to a new study released last week, and companies in the Washington area are no exception.
Companies in the District, Maryland, and Virginia collectively paid $27.6 billion to state and local coffers in fiscal 2013, up 3.8 percent from the $26.6 billion collected in 2012.
The state and local business tax burden increased 4.3 percent last year, to $671 billion, up from 3.9 percent a year earlier, and it was the third consecutive year of growth after consecutive years of shrinking bills in 2009 and 2010.
State taxes rose faster, 4.3 percent, than local taxes, 3.9 percent, according to a study conducted by professional services firm Ernst & Young and the Center on State Taxation, a tax policy group.
More than half of the District's tax revenue, 56 percent, comes from business taxes, while 36 percent of Maryland's tax revenue comes from firms.
Virginia, with 28 percent, generates the least tax revenue, proportionately, from entrepreneurs.
Much of the increase in tax revenue has been driven by a return to the previous level of company real estate values, researchers say, which has raised property taxes by 3.7 percent this year after three consecutive years of growth of less than 1 percent.
While large states such as California, New York and Texas account for a large share of these revenues, the same seems to be happening in the Washington area.
Companies in the District, Maryland, and Virginia collectively paid $10 billion in state and local property taxes last year, $9.6 billion more than in 2012 - a 4.2 percent increase over the previous year.
But the observed rebound in real estate values has no similar effect on state and local tax revenue growth in Maryland, where property taxes barely exceed one-fifth of companies "tax bills.
Virginia and the District of Columbia companies pay about half of their state and local tax bills in the form of property taxes.
"What's happening in Maryland is that so much of their real estate, especially the tax base around the District of Columbia, is owned either by the government or by non-profit organizations that don't pay property taxes," said Douglas Lindholm, executive director of the Center on State Taxation.
Thus, Maryland must rely much more on, for example, income taxes to pay for the same services that other states have.
The recent increase in business tax revenues cannot be fully attributed to the recovery in the real estate market.
Businessmen's incomes also seem to be on the mend, according to the data.
Companies in the region declared state corporate income taxes of $2.3 billion, $2.1 billion more than in 2012.
Maryland collected $1 billion in corporate income tax revenue, the most in the region.
Although trends are headed in the same direction, the tax burden on entrepreneurs at the local level is not increasing at the same rate in all three localities.
The District of Columbia grew at the same rate as the national average, 4.3 percent, while Maryland grew at a much faster rate, 4.9 percent.
Only Virginia saw below-average tax revenue growth of 4.1 percent.
Virginia had the lowest corporate income tax of the three jurisdictions (each with the same corporate rate), at 6 percent.
Maryland's corporate rate is 8.25 percent, while the District's is relatively high at 9.975 percent.
A similar study by the US Chamber of Commerce earlier this year found that Virginia has lower state and local business taxes and a generally more favorable business tax climate than Maryland.
The county was not evaluated in the study.
Despite its advantage, Virginia faces competitive pressure from its neighbor to the south.
North Carolina recently signed legislation lowering the corporate rate this year from 6.9 percent to 6 percent, the same as Virginia, and the rate will drop to 5 percent next year.
If the state continues to meet its tax revenue targets next year, the law could raise the business income tax rate to as much as 3 percent by 2017.
Meanwhile, small businesses in the Washington area seem to be feeling better, and thus paying more state and local taxes, according to a recent study.
Business taxes paid in the form of individual income taxes by small business owners - the transitional structure that most small firms are organized under - in the District of Columbia, Maryland, and Virginia rose 20 percent last year to $2.4 billion, a much faster rate of growth than business taxes as a whole.
Researchers say the trend and increase in business tax revenues across the country is likely to continue this year, with sales tax revenues in state and local governments up 6.2 percent in the first three quarters of 2014 compared to the same period last year.
But the Washington area may lag behind, as lower federal spending affects the region's labor market.
