On sale is the debut album of the band Royal Blood, the new hope of British rock, which has brought rock duos out of clubs and straight into stadiums.
The Royal Blood duo have only been on stage for a year, but already have a nomination for the BBC Music Award, a warm-up tour for Arctic Monkeys and a visit to the dressing room at a New York concert from Jimmy Page himself.
Their debut album of the same name received 100,000 pre-orders a few months before its release, and the contract for its release is in the portfolio of major label Warner Music.
Given the current lamentable situation in the music market, the situation is extraordinary, because it is not about the new Lana Del Rey or another sweet-voiced representative of the "new R'n'B," but about a duo of bullish-looking Brits playing with the level of volume and intensity that was last in vogue a couple of decades ago.
In general, the stakes for the first album were particularly high due to all of the above circumstances and have already been fully justified.
It is not for nothing that the duo have taken on a name that, until now, could only be encroached upon by desperate, hairy metalheads, and the blood of which kings, it seems to them, flows in their veins is also clear.
This is, of course, primarily about past Led Zeppelin heroes: like the great quartet, Royal Blood aims to shake the stagnant blood of British rock to new heights.
It is probably too early to make predictions about the success of this venture, but some things can already be said.
A dozen songs in just over thirty minutes is not so much a demonstration of phenomenal compositional talent as a confident and powerful declaration of intent.
Some of the virtues of individual numbers, of course, cannot be denied: say, the pilot single, "Out Of The Black," is characterized by the fact that it is remembered not as a melodic line, but as a drum part.
Musicians jokingly say that this song is easier to tap than to sing.
Also noteworthy is the powerful "Little Monster" and the album's closing track, "Better Strangers," with a Shakespearean quote in the title.
However, the truth is that each of these songs will sound great at a party of heavy rock fans, but when played in succession they merge into a more or less homogeneous canvas.
This is not necessarily a bad thing, or vice versa.
Royal Blood's strength lies in the fact that they do not claim to be the new Lennon and McCartney (rather they are being tagged as Motörhead's successors), but have brought numerous rock duos out of the indie club ghettos.
Their music, despite some variety, is made for stadiums, in a space designed for less than a couple of thousand people, it is obviously cramped.
The secret is partly in the ingenious use of bass, replacing the guitar in the familiar format invented in the early Zero The White Stripes.
However, it is not only about the instruments, but also about the approach to the composition of songs.
The heroes of the Zero retrorock struggled to get beyond the postmodern paradigm, and were extremely reluctant to recognize themselves not just as epigones, but as independent creative units.
Royal Blood, on the other hand, already sounds so powerful and brazen that it successfully drapes some of the secondary and hardness of the musical material.
After all, who said rock had to be smart?
