Deputies proposed to accelerate the entry into force of the law on personal data
In the event of the initiative's success, the data of Russians will not be stored on servers abroad from January 1, 2015
A draft law has been submitted to the State Duma, which provides for the postponement of the date of entry into force of the already adopted law on the personal data of Russians - from September 1, 2016 to January 1, 2015.
The initiative is located in the legislative activity database of the lower house.
It was sponsored by State Duma deputies Vadim Dengin, Yaroslav Nilov (LDPR), Evgeny Fedorov (United Russia), Vladimir Parakhin (Just Russia), and Alexander Yushchenko (CPRF).
Such a change, according to the authors of the initiative, will contribute to faster and more effective enforcement of the rights of citizens of the Russian Federation to the preservation of personal data and respect for the confidentiality of correspondence in information and telecommunication networks.
The law, the entry into force of which is hastened by parliamentarians, requires the storage on the territory of the Russian Federation of personal data of Russians processed through the Internet.
It also requires the recording, systematization, accumulation, storage, updating and retrieval of personal data of citizens of the Russian Federation in databases located on the territory of Russia, as well as the indication of the location of such databases.
In addition, the law gives Roskomnadzor the right, on the basis of a court decision, to restrict access to information processed in violation of the legislation of the Russian Federation in the field of personal data.
The law also proposes the creation of so-called "black lists" of offending sites - an automated information system "Register of violators of the rights of subjects of personal data."
This law was adopted by the State Duma in the summer.
The authors of the bill were Andrei Lugovoi and Vadim Dengin of the LDPR and Alexander Yushchenko of the CPRF.
Dengin and Yushchenko are also among the authors of the current bill to postpone the date of entry into force of the already adopted law.
Those who do not have data centers in Russia will have to pay for rent
Commenting on the bill submitted to the State Duma today, Leonid Levin, First Deputy Head of the Duma Committee for Information Policy, said that he sees no problem in postponing the date of entry into force of the law on the protection of personal data.
According to him, those companies that by January 1, 2015 will not have their own repositories of personal data of Russians on the territory of the Russian Federation will be able to rent them, for example, "from Rostelecom, which has repeatedly said that they are ready to lease their servers and are already providing their servers, from the Mail Group, from Western companies that are already providing their servers today."
"In addition, there are several independent data centers ready to cooperate in this area," he added.
"If companies decide to comply with the law and continue to operate in the Russian Federation, I don't see any problem - they will have the technological capacity to accommodate it," Levin concluded.
Controversial bill
Immediately after the publication of the draft law, the Russian Association of Electronic Communications expressed concern that, if the bill were adopted, Russians would no longer be able to use many global Internet services.
In particular, we are talking about online booking services for airline tickets and hotels.
According to the association, "the bill deprives the subjects of personal data - citizens of the Russian Federation - of the right to dispose of their own data, mandatorily determining that their recording, systematization, etc., should be provided only in databases located in the territory of the Russian Federation."
The RAEC statement emphasizes that a more effective measure would be to create a mechanism to inform the user about where his personal data is being recorded and systematized.
In this case, he will be able to choose on what territory these actions will be carried out.
The adoption of similar bills on the "localization" of personal data in other countries has led to the withdrawal of global services and significant economic losses.
