"Europrotocol" instead of a certificate from the traffic police
Payments on a helmet can be received without a certificate from the traffic police - so the Central Bank intends to stimulate the introduction of "europrotocol" in Russia.
The Bank of Russia has developed a draft instruction, according to which, starting from September 1 of this year, an insured motorist will be able to receive payments on a helmet without a certificate from the traffic police.
It is true, however, that this is only the case when the accident was processed according to the "euro protocol" without the involvement of the traffic police.
That is, if only two vehicles were involved in an accident, there are no physically injured persons, the damage does not exceed the established limit, and both drivers have reached an agreement on who is responsible for the accident.
From 2 August, the limit for payments under the "europrotocol" amounts to 50 thousand roubles, and from 1 October in Moscow, St. Petersburg, as well as in Moscow and Leningrad Oblasts, it will be raised to 400 thousand roubles.
The bottom line is that often, even in the case of minor damage, in a situation where an accident can be processed according to the "euro protocol," the drivers involved in the accident call the traffic police.
After all, it was impossible to get a refund on a Casco policy without a certificate from the traffic police.
The parameters set out in the draft directive are intended precisely to remove this obstacle to the implementation of the "europrotocol" in Russia.
According to them, the maximum payout on a helmet in connection with an accident, issued without traffic police officers, should not be lower than the limit under the "europrotocol."
But, at the same time, it cannot be higher than the limit set out in the contract of insurance of the Casco.
The idea is certainly useful and theoretically capable of relieving both traffic officers and roads.
But neither motorists nor insurers are likely to be enthused by it.
The latter are already talking about the serious threat of an increase in fraud, which could result from the introduction of new rules on the payment of helmets.
As for drivers, it is hard to imagine what work will have to be done to overcome Russia's traditional conservatism.
In most cases, the driver will wait hours for an inspector to process a minor accident because it is so reliable.
And it is not yet known what will be easier - to defeat the fraudsters or to convince drivers of the reliability of the "europrotocol."
The savings certificate will be made registered and irrevocable
The Ministry of Finance wants to ban bearer savings certificates, but will allow banks to make them the equivalent of irrevocable deposits.
The Ministry of Finance is preparing a bill that will ban bearer savings certificates.
Recently, this instrument has gained popularity, because the rates are higher than those on bank deposits.
The point is that bearer savings certificates are not covered by the deposit insurance system, and they are cheaper for the bank because it does not have to contribute to the Deposit Insurance Agency (DIA).
The piquancy of the situation is that this step is planned to be taken because of small and medium-sized banks distributing such certificates, and Sberbank and Bank of Moscow, which, according to DIA estimates, control 98% of the profile market, will suffer from it.
Moreover, the Bank of Moscow's share, according to the agency's calculations, is about 3.5%.
The problem, the DIA explains, is that customers of a small bank who have purchased such a certificate, in case of revocation of its license, try to get money from the DIA.
Some savers, lacking financial literacy and buying bearer savings certificates, may assume that their investments are insured.
The justified absence of insurance payments on these certificates in case of revocation of the bank's license may lead to misunderstandings and social tensions.
In the practice of the agency, there were cases when holders of bearer certificates tried to recover insurance indemnity through the courts, "the DIA stated.
The problem is, of course, far-fetched.
After all, no one will pay buyers of certificates anyway, because they have no right to compensation from the state under the law.
If the issue were that the instrument was not insured by the DIA, metal accounts in which citizens "funds are recorded in grams of one of the four metals - gold, silver, platinum and palladium - would also be banned.
After all, these accounts also do not fall into the deposit insurance system, but their existence has not yet been compromised.
The point is most likely that bearer certificates are a very convenient security that can actually act as quasi-custodians.
At the same time, their movement is almost uncontrollable: any client of the bank can buy a certificate, hand it over to any citizen, and before cashing out, such a certificate can be changed by many owners.
It is no accident that the draft law stipulates that a savings certificate must be a registered security, which must be kept in a depository.
And, in order to sweeten the pill for banks, such certificates are allowed to be issued without the right to early repayment.
That is, the equivalent of the irrevocable deposit that bankers have long dreamed of is being introduced.
