Two unions meet
The high-level talks in Minsk did not solve the problems for which they were convened, but gave rise to a new format: the leaders of the European Union met with the leaders of the future Eurasian Economic Union.
Albeit alarming (the situation around Ukraine cannot be delayed), the leaders of the EU and the Customs Union discussed for the first time a number of "hot issues."
Whether such a structure can work effectively is unclear; but it is clear who has taken the cream off this summit.
Questions in this respect disappeared on the evening of 26 August, when Belarusians, and then other Eurasians and Europeans, saw the new President Lukashenka on television news.
The Belarusian leader was an example of polished politeness, the behavior of a man who has just hit the jackpot - and is planning a dignified retirement in high society.
How Maidan Lukashenko Helped
The arrival in Minsk of three major European commissioners (EU ministers), who met with Lukashenko and allowed him to address a final briefing on their behalf, is not merely legitimizing a president with 20 years of experience.
This is an application for recognition of Minsk as a full-fledged subject of European politics and the main mediator of the Ukrainian crisis.
Senior analyst at the Belarusian Institute for Strategic Studies, Denis Melyantsov, is confident that Brussels will no longer be able to talk to Minsk in the same tone as before.
"The fact that Catherine Ashton met face-to-face with Lukashenko gives grounds to believe that relations with the EU will continue to thaw," he told Ogonyok.
There is a hidden part of this iceberg: Belarusian authorities began preparing for a breakthrough long before the November Maidan in Kyiv, in the summer of 2013.
"Results have also been achieved with the EU: successful negotiations on visa facilitation and readmission, dialogues on modernization," lists the Ogonyok interlocutor, "and negotiations on international security were held with the United States.
The States even lifted some sanctions.
As for the Ukrainian events, they themselves and the reaction to them by the Belarusian leadership only spurred this process.
On the one hand, Minsk managed to maintain relations with Ukraine - warm enough not to lose much in mutual trade, and President Poroshenko could come to Belarus for talks.
On the other hand, the Belarusian leader, who de jure did not recognize Crimea's annexation to Russia and called for punishing pro-Russian militias in Donbas with the utmost severity, did not quarrel with Moscow.
Minsk has not left the Customs Union or the CSTO, and a Russian air base is located in Baranovichi.
Brussels and Washington noticed Minsk's balanced position on the Ukrainian issue - and appreciated it, Belarusian experts are convinced.
How successful Lukashenko's move toward political diversification turns out to be will be seen by how often Minsk will be able to host meetings in the EU + CU format in the near future.
The press service of the EU High Representative for Foreign Policy and Diplomacy, Catherine Ashton, was unable to respond promptly to questions about what Brussels expects from the relationship in the new format.
Ashton's press secretary, Maja Kosyancic, only told Ogonyok that this topic is not a priority against the background of resolving issues of war and peace.
At the same time, there have been reports that Kazakhstan may become the next venue for a meeting on the Ukrainian issue with the participation of top officials in the new format.
The straw that broke the camel's back for Minsk was the statement by President Nursultan Nazarbayev, in which he admitted that he had been personally asked to do so by representatives of the European Union.
Nevertheless, at the final briefing, Alexander Lukashenko made it clear that all sides are not opposed to Minsk remaining a central venue for meetings both in the Russia-OSCE-Ukraine format and at the level of heads of state and high representatives of the European Commission.
This means that "Europe's last dictator" is gaining the status of a fully hands-on European leader who is helping to solve a global problem.
Europe's Farmer's Best Friend
The very composition of the EU delegation, which included the European Commissioners for Trade and Energy, led to the conclusion that the main reason for the summit was not the tragic situation in Donbas, but the economy.
Indeed, the timetable for future negotiations on gas supplies and overcoming the concerns of the CU countries on Ukraine's association agreement with the EU, which was drawn up at the meeting, looks more ambitious than the peaceful declarations without specific dates and figures.
Trade Commissioner Karl De Gucht, however, indicated that EU representatives "came to Minsk to seek a solution to the political crisis, which has economic consequences, not the other way around."
It seems, however, that the crisis in Ukraine is also working for Belarus economically.
Its consequences - and, above all, mutual sanctions between the West and Russia - give Minsk, which is still under sanctions pressure, much-awaited room for maneuver.
According to Yaroslav Romanchuk, Head of the Mises Research Center and former presidential candidate of Belarus, European investors are actively interested in Belarus "ability to supply agricultural products to the Russian Federation, circumventing the sanctions.
At the same time, supply chains are being put forward, for which Vladimir Putin scolded Minsk at the summit.
