They have been working out schemes for the supply of goods, including from Poland, Germany, Lithuania, for a long time, and today these schemes have been destroyed.
Russian businesses desperately need to somehow restore them, even through the intermediary of Belarusian structures.
The second plot, the expert continues, is connected with the fact that many Ukrainian companies are not averse to setting up production in Belarus from Ukrainian raw materials, also with a focus on the Russian market.
Ukrainian producers have about $4 billion in exports to Russia, and Belarusian production and trading schemes may now be in high demand. "
According to Romanchuk, the role of host of the EU-CU negotiation platform is ideal for Lukashenko in terms of developing economic ties with Europe as well.
He recalls that losses to the EU agricultural sector from Moscow's sanctions are estimated at 5-10 billion euros, while the European Commission has so far offered farmers only 125 million euros in compensation.
The Belarusian president could propose that Brussels work together to minimize the impact on European farmers.
This could raise Lukashenko's standing in the EU to an all-time high.
