Boredom sinful
Frank Miller and Robert Rodriguez's film Sin City 2: A Woman Worth Killing for has not revolutionized the way one would expect it to.
The first Sin City (2005), shot with minimal but symbolic participation by Quentin Tarantino, revolutionized the relationship between film, comics, and literary noir.
The sequel is also revolutionary in its own way: in the sense that it destroys the thesis-antithesis-synthesis chain that is fundamental to modern thinking (meaning the noir universe by thesis, and the comics cosmos by antithesis).
From now on, it should read "thesis - antithesis - chaos."
Sin City 2 is chaotic on both a dramatic and philosophical level: both times it is chaotic in the bad sense of the word.
Yes, some of the characters are familiar from the first "City," though Marv (Mickey Rourke), I remember, ended his life on an electric chair, and here, nothing, only manages to snatch knives and other axes from the air in the role of such a folk band.
But the old people are literally elbowed by newcomers, as if they had broken into the city from some other film, the meaning and plot of which the audience is asked not to worry about.
Thus, the story, shamelessly cut off by the authors at the most interesting place, has a super-lucky gambler, Johnny (Joseph Gordon-Levitt).
Her own is with the lustful-frigid Eve Lord (Eva Green) and the vengeful Dwight (Josh Brolin).
But this confusion, in which Dwight is, say, indistinguishable from Johnny - all the more so because the characters "faces, like other body parts, are swept away with inexorable regularity - is not trouble, not even half-trouble.
These are not people, but we understand that they are the archetypes of noir: the fateful bitch, the overconfident gambler, the "honey trap" sex detective, the corrupt senate ghoulish.
Well, and when an archetype waltzes with an archetype and an archetype chases, it is no longer a movie, but rather an abstract painting.
And to ask abstract painting questions about the logic of the subject is simply ridiculous.
Moreover, even in this tumultuous world, there is something permanent.
The fighting whores of the first "City" still maintain a perimeter defense against the forces of darkness besieging their native slums.
And the ghost of Detective Hartigan is gone, and there will be a glimpse of the light, and Bruce Willis is always nice to look at.
The main problem with Sin City 2 is another.
Frank Miller was good at combining comics and noir as a graphic designer, and as a director at turning over the idea of how to bring comics to the screen.
Comics and noir are two aggressively opposite "realities."
The comic book phenomenon in its modern form was born in the late 1920 "s, at the same time that Dashil Hammett's novels Blood Harvest (1929), The Maltese Falcon (1930), and The Glass Key (1931) created the canon of noir, then called hard-boiled school.
Well, or pulp fiction.
Comics have given Hollywood dozens of characters, from Popeye the spinach eater, Superman, Batman and detective Dick Tracy, to the Hulk, Thor, Spider-Man, and other "Avengers."
But there was something defective about any comic-inspired film: the characters stubbornly did not want to be outgrown by onscreen flesh, and remained feigns in the "real" world surrounding them willy-nilly.
Simply put, they were utterly devoid of "existence."
Noir, by contrast, is the most existential genre of world literature.
After the world wars, the traditional novel - with its experiences, characters, family scandals, and historical background - lost all credibility.
Which Forsytes, which Thibault and Rougon-Macquarie, which even Bolkonsky and Rostov are even conceivable after Verdun, Auschwitz, and Hiroshima?
Such a novel mutated peacefully into a soap opera format, and a criminal - that is, by definition marginal - novel rose to the level of philosophical prose.
Hammett learned what it was like to be a front-line nurse.
He was a communist.
As, incidentally, were at least such pillars of the genre as writers Horace McCoy and Jim Thompson, directors Jules Dassin, Joseph Losey, and Edward Dmitrik.
So the noir whose archetype they set is, first, crude and cynical, and, second, strictly social.
This is almost an American version of socialist realism.
The first Sin City was remarkable precisely because it unnaturally but organically combined comics with noir.
For the first time on the screen, the comic came to life, not shy of its graphic nature, rather than pretending to be a "real" film.
The gloom of a venal world, where a cardinal ordered murders and a senator covered up a monstrous sadistic son, was worthy of Hammett's pen.
And picturesque details like the severed heads with which the sadist decorated his nest, the pen of the genius James Ellroy, the author of "The Black Orchid" and the best - that is, declaratively nauseating - representative of neonuar.
Sin City 2 is not even a retreat, but a capitulation of Miller-Rodriguez's radical stylistic style to the comic tradition.
Perhaps much of this is due to 3D technology.
When you watch the second Sin City, you feel like you are trapped in a glass ball, inside of which snow falls over a toy clown.
More often than not, though, it's not snow, but bloody bumps, but by and large, what's the difference?
But there is nothing to say about sociality.
After all, it is possible only when somewhere, somewhere, we sometimes have a normal world, albeit on the edge of a dirty swamp, where it is possible to return a girl who has walked a crooked path or, say, to tell inconsolable parents that her killer has been punished.
When there is no room in the city of sin for anything but sin, then sin is no longer a sin, but a norm.
Boring as any norm.
The chaos of Sin City 2 is simply boring.
To be fair, the domestic release gave this fresh sin a small but glove.
The credits warn: the film contains harmful scenes of smoking.
In relation to the spectacle, in the most vegetarian episode of which a person's fingers are broken with forceps, this smacks of hellish humour.
Hammett would have liked it.
