Anger turned out to be man's most universal and functional emotion
Angry facial expressions are biologically universal for humanity, and every organ and muscle group involved in their creation is not accidental, but an additional means of expressing power and threat, scientists in Australia and the United States have found.
Their findings were reported in the journal Evolution and Human Behavior, and can be summarized in a press release from the University of California, Santa Barbara.
Angry facial expressions - furrowed and lowered eyebrows, stretched lips, swollen nostrils - are the same in all cultures, and even born-blind children who have never seen it do so, notes the study's lead author, Aaron Sell.
As part of a major research project on the nature of anger, scientists have found that this emotion was created to effectively manage disputes during conflict.
The more physical damage one person can inflict on another, the more power he has to dictate his terms, and he communicates this to his interlocutor through anger.
The researchers also found support for their other hypothesis: physically strong people are more likely to get angry and turn to physical abuse, consider themselves entitled to impose disadvantageous conditions on others, and prefer violent methods of conflict resolution to peaceful ones.
Starting from the premise that anger is primarily an "emotion of bargaining," the researchers decided that the movements of each of the seven muscle groups that produce angry facial expressions should make the angry individual more powerful and dangerous in the eyes of the interlocutor - and thus force the interlocutor to agree to his terms as soon as possible to avoid conflict.
To test this hypothesis, the researchers simulated faces on a computer with or without each of the seven elements of an angry face, and showed them to the informants.
Although lowered eyebrows or an outstretched chin alone did not make the face angry, the study's participants unanimously agreed that a person with such traits was physically stronger.
Human anger, like that of animals, expresses a threat: an exaggerated manifestation of self-power that compels consent and submission.
A man inflates his nostrils and presses his lips for the same purpose as a frog that puffs itself up, or a baboon that shows off its fangs.
"Anger" is triggered by the interlocutor's refusal to accept the situation, and the person immediately assumes a form that best demonstrates to the other side the consequences of that refusal.
But the most striking thing is that none of the components of an angry face are arbitrary, they all express the same thing, "anthropologist John Tooby noted.
The Ministry of Communications has offered to allocate 250 million roubles to the television and radio company "Crimea"
The Ministry of Communications has proposed to allocate 250 million roubles from the federal budget in 2014 to the autonomous non-profit organization Crimea Television and Radio Company.
This is stated in a draft government decree prepared by the agency, which has been reviewed by Lenta.ru.
According to the explanatory note to the project, subsidies from the federal budget will be used "to cover the costs of creating conditions for large-scale information coverage of the social and economic situation and the development of a modern information space on the territory of the Republic of Crimea, including the purchase of equipment."
In particular, the allocated funds will be used to retrofit a hardware and studio unit, video walls, a central hardware and video server room.
Plans are also under way to acquire a mobile television station and a satellite transmitter.
In addition, the company will use the allocated funds to pay for the use of a fiber-optic communication line (VOLS) and the repair of the energy system.
Subsidies will be provided within the limits of the federal budget allocated to the Ministry of Communications.
The state television and radio broadcasting company Crimea was established in 1959 and broadcasts in seven languages: Ukrainian, Russian, Crimean Tatar, German, Greek, Bulgarian and Armenian.
Today, the television and radio broadcasting company's television signal coverage is more than 75 percent of the peninsula's territory.
In 2011, Crimea Television and Radio Company received a license to broadcast in digital format.
